      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat(slack): support per-channel replyToMode",
        "body": "## Summary\n- add `replyToMode` to Slack per-channel config/schema/types and generated channel metadata\n- resolve channel config before account/chat-type fallback when determining Slack reply/thread mode\n- pass resolved channel config through the regex-mention reroute path\n- document `channels.slack.channels.<id>.replyToMode`\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n**Behavior or issue addressed:** Slack per-channel `replyToMode` overrides account/chat-type fallback for a real channel-style Slack inbound event. With account/chat-type set to `all` and channel override set to `off`, the prepared reply stays top-level (`MessageThreadId=<unset>`, `replyToThreadTs=<unset>`). The regex mention reroute path keeps the same channel override.\n\n**Real environment tested:** Repo/branch `truiem-bot:slack-channel-reply-to-mode`, commit `27f8056aafa8e52b9aaabc7daf2241ab7d2c84d6`, local OpenClaw workspace checkout on Node via `tsx`. Slack workspace/channel/user ids used from the real installed Slack workspace: `T04URFH9M9C`, `C0B252YDK9D`, `U04VANQ55Q9`. Private names/tokens redacted. No live OpenClaw config was mutated and the gateway was not restarted.\n\n**Exact steps or command run after this patch:**\n1. Configure account/chat-type fallback to thread channel replies: `replyToMode=all`, `replyToModeByChatType.channel=all`.\n2. Configure channel override: `channels.C0B252YDK9D.requireMention=false`, `channels.C0B252YDK9D.replyToMode=off`.\n3. Configure regex mention path: `messages.groupChat.mentionPatterns=[/\\bbill\\b/]`.\n4. Run the PR branch through the production Slack message preparation path:\n   ```\n   node --import tsx /tmp/slack-channel-reply-proof-run.mts\n   ```\n\n**Evidence after fix:** Console output from the command above:\n```\nREAL BEHAVIOR PROOF: Slack per-channel replyToMode override\nconfig: account.replyToMode=all, replyToModeByChatType.channel=all\nconfig: channels[C0B252YDK9D].requireMention=false, replyToMode=off\nconfig: messages.groupChat.mentionPatterns=[/\\bbill\\b/]\nCASE=implicit-channel-message\nteam=T04URFH9M9C channel=C0B252YDK9D user=U04VANQ55Q9\ninput.text=\"proof: requireMention false channel should reply top-level, not thread\"\nprepared.replyToMode=off\nctx.ChatType=channel\nctx.WasMentioned=false\nctx.MessageThreadId=<unset>\nctx.SessionKey=agent:main:slack:channel:c0b252ydk9d\nroute.replyToThreadTs=<unset>\nRESULT=PASS channel override won; reply will be top-level\nCASE=regex-mention-reroute\nteam=T04URFH9M9C channel=C0B252YDK9D user=U04VANQ55Q9\ninput.text=\"Bill proof: regex mention reroute must still stay top-level\"\nprepared.replyToMode=off\nctx.ChatType=channel\nctx.WasMentioned=true\nctx.MessageThreadId=<unset>\nctx.SessionKey=agent:main:slack:channel:c0b252ydk9d\nroute.replyToThreadTs=<unset>\nRESULT=PASS channel override won; reply will be top-level\n```\n\n**Observed result after fix:** Both cases used `prepared.replyToMode=off` from the channel override even though account/chat-type fallback was `all`. Both cases left `MessageThreadId` and `replyToThreadTs` unset, so OpenClaw would reply top-level instead of threading. The regex mention reroute case also preserved the channel override.\n\n**What was not tested:** I did not deploy this branch into the live gateway or send live Slack messages from the bot, to avoid mutating live config or restarting the user's running OpenClaw gateway during review. The proof exercises the production Slack preparation/routing path locally with real workspace/channel/user ids and redacted private data.\n\n## Tests\n- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs run --config test/vitest/vitest.extension-slack.config.ts extensions/slack/src/config-schema.test.ts extensions/slack/src/monitor/message-handler/prepare.test.ts` — 89 passed\n- `pnpm tsgo:extensions:test` — passed\n- `pnpm config:schema:gen && pnpm config:channels:gen` — passed\n",
